WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:17.062 align:middle line:10%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:17.062 --> 00:00:19.020 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA MEREDITH: Get
a pen and some paper out

00:00:19.020 --> 00:00:20.436 align:middle line:10%
because you're
going to learn more

00:00:20.436 --> 00:00:22.860 align:middle line:10%
about your body's
ecosystem in one hour

00:00:22.860 --> 00:00:24.630 align:middle line:10%
than you ever thought possible.

00:00:24.630 --> 00:00:28.320 align:middle line:10%
Compton Rom is a microbiologist
who extended his knowledge far

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:31.570 align:middle line:10%
beyond his master's degree into
the worlds of interconnected

00:00:31.570 --> 00:00:33.410 align:middle line:10%
information systems,
which brings

00:00:33.410 --> 00:00:35.720 align:middle line:10%
a new light to the
world of microbes.

00:00:35.720 --> 00:00:38.610 align:middle line:84%
Compton says that our bodies
cannot sustain good health

00:00:38.610 --> 00:00:42.060 align:middle line:84%
without good microbes, and that
we must learn to respect them.

00:00:42.060 --> 00:00:44.040 align:middle line:84%
Toward that end, he
founded a company

00:00:44.040 --> 00:00:47.090 align:middle line:84%
that uses microbes and
frequencies to recover

00:00:47.090 --> 00:00:47.590 align:middle line:90%
our health.

00:00:47.590 --> 00:00:51.040 align:middle line:84%
And I have to say,
his work is absolutely

00:00:51.040 --> 00:00:52.790 align:middle line:90%
mind-altering in my book.

00:00:52.790 --> 00:00:55.500 align:middle line:84%
I think this is one of the most
fascinating subjects of all.

00:00:55.500 --> 00:00:58.740 align:middle line:84%
But before we even get
going on the microbes,

00:00:58.740 --> 00:01:01.370 align:middle line:84%
let's talk a little bit
about your own background,

00:01:01.370 --> 00:01:05.550 align:middle line:84%
and it was a convoluted path
arriving where you are now.

00:01:05.550 --> 00:01:07.780 align:middle line:84%
And just tell us a
little bit about that.

00:01:07.780 --> 00:01:10.110 align:middle line:84%
>>COMPTON ROM: Well, I
actually got my start

00:01:10.110 --> 00:01:12.510 align:middle line:84%
by going to medical school at
the University of Michigan.

00:01:12.510 --> 00:01:16.010 align:middle line:10%
And I finished up my schooling
by getting a Master's Degree

00:01:16.010 --> 00:01:19.530 align:middle line:10%
in Microbiology at Michigan
State University, where

00:01:19.530 --> 00:01:24.050 align:middle line:10%
I worked under the auspices
of the Microbial Ecology

00:01:24.050 --> 00:01:27.890 align:middle line:10%
Center, which looked at
the beneficial microbes

00:01:27.890 --> 00:01:31.020 align:middle line:10%
and how did they degrade toxins
in the external environment.

00:01:31.020 --> 00:01:33.110 align:middle line:10%
But how also microbes
were really important

00:01:33.110 --> 00:01:34.530 align:middle line:10%
in agriculture.

00:01:34.530 --> 00:01:36.770 align:middle line:84%
So from there, I
thought I was going

00:01:36.770 --> 00:01:38.440 align:middle line:84%
to get a career
in biotechnology,

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:41.230 align:middle line:84%
but I fell into the
laps of IBM and I

00:01:41.230 --> 00:01:45.100 align:middle line:84%
started working for the
pharmaceutical companies

00:01:45.100 --> 00:01:49.530 align:middle line:84%
looking over gobs of data and
analyzing data, and seeing

00:01:49.530 --> 00:01:51.510 align:middle line:84%
where things worked
and where things didn't

00:01:51.510 --> 00:01:55.444 align:middle line:84%
work based on the
research out there.

00:01:55.444 --> 00:01:57.360 align:middle line:84%
And then I took a path
thinking, oh, you know,

00:01:57.360 --> 00:01:58.859 align:middle line:84%
the internet was
really good for me,

00:01:58.859 --> 00:02:04.530 align:middle line:84%
so I started working with IBM
again and being farmed out

00:02:04.530 --> 00:02:07.690 align:middle line:84%
for search engine companies
like Google and Yahoo,

00:02:07.690 --> 00:02:09.940 align:middle line:84%
and a little company
called Inktomi.

00:02:09.940 --> 00:02:13.650 align:middle line:84%
And that was when I
started getting access

00:02:13.650 --> 00:02:17.340 align:middle line:84%
to all these university archives
and university research.

00:02:17.340 --> 00:02:20.000 align:middle line:84%
And I really started
looking into the research

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.950 align:middle line:84%
of alternative science and
how they became validated

00:02:23.950 --> 00:02:26.010 align:middle line:90%
through the scientific research.

00:02:26.010 --> 00:02:29.330 align:middle line:84%
And as we know, a lot of these
scientific research papers

00:02:29.330 --> 00:02:32.970 align:middle line:84%
have been buried and not really
being shown to the public.

00:02:32.970 --> 00:02:34.750 align:middle line:90%
But I had full access to them.

00:02:34.750 --> 00:02:39.590 align:middle line:84%
And I knew that natural herbs
can actually-- back then,

00:02:39.590 --> 00:02:41.460 align:middle line:90%
they were curing AIDS.

00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:44.260 align:middle line:84%
And I knew microbes were
actually killing viruses,

00:02:44.260 --> 00:02:46.930 align:middle line:84%
that you didn't need
vaccines to kill the viruses.

00:02:46.930 --> 00:02:48.940 align:middle line:90%
You can actually use microbes.

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:50.720 align:middle line:84%
And so from that
research, that's

00:02:50.720 --> 00:02:54.430 align:middle line:84%
how I started a little company
called Ascended Health.

00:02:54.430 --> 00:02:57.890 align:middle line:84%
The Native Americans, they
actually traded in this earth.

00:02:57.890 --> 00:02:59.690 align:middle line:90%
They actually have edible clays.

00:02:59.690 --> 00:03:03.150 align:middle line:84%
Every tribe, every medicine
man has his own set

00:03:03.150 --> 00:03:06.910 align:middle line:84%
of herbs that he likes
to use, but they also

00:03:06.910 --> 00:03:08.720 align:middle line:90%
have edible clays.

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:15.560 align:middle line:84%
And you actually saw this
during the hurricane in Haiti,

00:03:15.560 --> 00:03:19.060 align:middle line:84%
when all the people on
CNN were eating mud pies.

00:03:19.060 --> 00:03:21.702 align:middle line:84%
They were actually eating
clay to sustain them.

00:03:21.702 --> 00:03:23.660 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Now see, we
watched that and thought,

00:03:23.660 --> 00:03:25.730 align:middle line:84%
oh, these poor people
are having to eat dirt.

00:03:25.730 --> 00:03:28.360 align:middle line:84%
We didn't understand
that there were some--

00:03:28.360 --> 00:03:28.830 align:middle line:84%
>>ROM: They were
getting minerals.

00:03:28.830 --> 00:03:30.180 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: -components
of nutrition there.

00:03:30.180 --> 00:03:30.890 align:middle line:90%
>>ROM: That's right.

00:03:30.890 --> 00:03:31.806 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Interesting.

00:03:31.806 --> 00:03:33.900 align:middle line:84%
>>ROM: You go down to
the Peru, to the Amazon,

00:03:33.900 --> 00:03:36.160 align:middle line:84%
and you look at
the birds in Manu

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:40.190 align:middle line:84%
eating the clay off
the side of the rivers.

00:03:40.190 --> 00:03:41.840 align:middle line:84%
And there's a big
tourist attraction.

00:03:41.840 --> 00:03:43.970 align:middle line:84%
But they don't really tell
them that the reason why

00:03:43.970 --> 00:03:47.410 align:middle line:84%
the birds are eating the clay
is because the clay is filled

00:03:47.410 --> 00:03:49.910 align:middle line:84%
with bentonite and
it coats their system

00:03:49.910 --> 00:03:53.460 align:middle line:84%
so they can eat the
poisonous seeds in the Amazon

00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:55.364 align:middle line:84%
that the other
animals can't eat,

00:03:55.364 --> 00:03:56.530 align:middle line:90%
and they don't get poisoned.

00:03:56.530 --> 00:03:58.370 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, see, this is
what I love about your work.

00:03:58.370 --> 00:04:00.453 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't matter where
we go in the conversation,

00:04:00.453 --> 00:04:02.960 align:middle line:84%
we get all these
incredible side notes.

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:06.900 align:middle line:84%
And so now on a
large theme, let's

00:04:06.900 --> 00:04:09.750 align:middle line:84%
go to the world of
microbes and give us

00:04:09.750 --> 00:04:12.710 align:middle line:84%
an introduction in
terms of how long

00:04:12.710 --> 00:04:15.680 align:middle line:84%
they've been here as opposed
to as how they survive,

00:04:15.680 --> 00:04:19.760 align:middle line:84%
how the world really will
be their way or the highway.

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:23.000 align:middle line:84%
>>ROM: Well, let's go
over the latest science.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:25.060 align:middle line:84%
I always like to start
everything else out

00:04:25.060 --> 00:04:29.070 align:middle line:84%
in basic fundamental science,
and then go to the esoteric.

00:04:29.070 --> 00:04:31.590 align:middle line:84%
So all the work
that we do is based

00:04:31.590 --> 00:04:33.200 align:middle line:90%
on solid scientific research.

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:38.220 align:middle line:84%
If it's not researched, if it's
not validated by scientists

00:04:38.220 --> 00:04:42.750 align:middle line:84%
and basically printed
in a scientific journal,

00:04:42.750 --> 00:04:45.160 align:middle line:84%
then I don't usually
pursue that line of work.

00:04:45.160 --> 00:04:49.970 align:middle line:84%
Well lately, since 2003, there's
all this new science coming out

00:04:49.970 --> 00:04:53.010 align:middle line:84%
that microbes are very
beneficial to human life.

00:04:53.010 --> 00:04:57.200 align:middle line:84%
And it's now called
the Microbiome Project.

00:04:57.200 --> 00:05:00.590 align:middle line:84%
And it started out through
the Genome Project,

00:05:00.590 --> 00:05:03.850 align:middle line:84%
when they were starting
to study and sequence

00:05:03.850 --> 00:05:05.480 align:middle line:90%
the DNA of the human being.

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:08.110 align:middle line:84%
And they finally sequenced
the DNA of the human being.

00:05:08.110 --> 00:05:10.380 align:middle line:90%
And they go, wow, we did it.

00:05:10.380 --> 00:05:12.620 align:middle line:84%
We sequenced the DNA
in a human being,

00:05:12.620 --> 00:05:15.840 align:middle line:84%
let's see how many genes are in
humans, because humans are so

00:05:15.840 --> 00:05:17.710 align:middle line:84%
evolved they must
have more genes

00:05:17.710 --> 00:05:19.360 align:middle line:90%
than any animal in the world.

00:05:19.360 --> 00:05:24.770 align:middle line:84%
Well, it turns out that the
little Arabidopsis plant, which

00:05:24.770 --> 00:05:27.440 align:middle line:84%
is a little tiny plant
that grows in the cold,

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:30.580 align:middle line:90%
has about 128,000 genes.

00:05:30.580 --> 00:05:33.650 align:middle line:84%
And the humans only
had as many genes

00:05:33.650 --> 00:05:36.470 align:middle line:84%
as the little lowly
fly, the Drosophila fly,

00:05:36.470 --> 00:05:38.600 align:middle line:90%
probably like 30,000 genes.

00:05:38.600 --> 00:05:40.520 align:middle line:84%
So the scientists
were wondering,

00:05:40.520 --> 00:05:44.860 align:middle line:84%
how could a complex organism
like the human being

00:05:44.860 --> 00:05:49.450 align:middle line:84%
exist versus a little
organism like the fly

00:05:49.450 --> 00:05:53.430 align:middle line:84%
exist together and be
so different; but yet,

00:05:53.430 --> 00:05:57.080 align:middle line:84%
the amount of genes that
they have is the same.

00:05:57.080 --> 00:05:59.935 align:middle line:84%
And these scientists
are saying, well,

00:05:59.935 --> 00:06:01.310 align:middle line:84%
there's got to be
something else.

00:06:01.310 --> 00:06:04.720 align:middle line:84%
So let's study the
microbes in the body.

00:06:04.720 --> 00:06:07.400 align:middle line:84%
And they thought that it was
going to be a little project,

00:06:07.400 --> 00:06:10.130 align:middle line:84%
but they found something
really fascinating.

00:06:10.130 --> 00:06:15.460 align:middle line:84%
They found that out of all the
living cells in this ecosystem

00:06:15.460 --> 00:06:17.750 align:middle line:84%
we call the human
body, they found

00:06:17.750 --> 00:06:21.060 align:middle line:84%
that there was over 100
trillion living cells

00:06:21.060 --> 00:06:23.820 align:middle line:84%
in this ecosystem we
call the human body.

00:06:23.820 --> 00:06:26.510 align:middle line:84%
But when you count all the
human cells, all the skin cells,

00:06:26.510 --> 00:06:29.070 align:middle line:84%
the eye cells, the cardiac
cells, the hair cells,

00:06:29.070 --> 00:06:31.172 align:middle line:84%
there's only 10
trillion of those cells.

00:06:31.172 --> 00:06:32.630 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Do the
math on that then.

00:06:32.630 --> 00:06:33.590 align:middle line:90%
>>ROM: Do the math.

00:06:33.590 --> 00:06:36.290 align:middle line:84%
So only 10 trillion out
of 100 trillion cells

00:06:36.290 --> 00:06:37.430 align:middle line:90%
were human cells.

00:06:37.430 --> 00:06:41.750 align:middle line:84%
That meant 90% of the living
cells in this ecosystem

00:06:41.750 --> 00:06:43.400 align:middle line:84%
in the human body
weren't even human.

00:06:43.400 --> 00:06:45.110 align:middle line:84%
They were actually
microbial cells.

00:06:45.110 --> 00:06:47.690 align:middle line:90%
They're made of mostly bacteria.

00:06:47.690 --> 00:06:49.770 align:middle line:84%
But we have viruses,
we have parasites,

00:06:49.770 --> 00:06:53.700 align:middle line:84%
we have fungi in our
bodies, and they all

00:06:53.700 --> 00:06:55.570 align:middle line:90%
call this body our home.

00:06:55.570 --> 00:06:57.800 align:middle line:84%
So I started reading
all this material.

00:06:57.800 --> 00:07:00.960 align:middle line:84%
I found that actually
fascinating that only 10%

00:07:00.960 --> 00:07:02.940 align:middle line:90%
of the human body is human.

00:07:02.940 --> 00:07:05.140 align:middle line:84%
But then when the
scientists were going,

00:07:05.140 --> 00:07:06.250 align:middle line:90%
well, let's study the DNA.

00:07:06.250 --> 00:07:10.050 align:middle line:84%
I bet 98% of the DNA in
the human body is human.

00:07:10.050 --> 00:07:13.100 align:middle line:84%
Well, guess the percentage
of the DNA is human.

00:07:13.100 --> 00:07:13.760 align:middle line:90%
2%.

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:14.340 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: 2.

00:07:14.340 --> 00:07:15.080 align:middle line:90%
>>ROM: 2.

00:07:15.080 --> 00:07:16.010 align:middle line:90%
So do the math.

00:07:16.010 --> 00:07:17.160 align:middle line:90%
2% to 10%.

00:07:17.160 --> 00:07:19.820 align:middle line:84%
We're only 2%
human or 10% human.

00:07:19.820 --> 00:07:21.930 align:middle line:84%
But the fact of the
matter is, the result

00:07:21.930 --> 00:07:25.330 align:middle line:84%
is the majority of our body
doesn't come from our genes.

00:07:25.330 --> 00:07:26.874 align:middle line:90%
It comes from our environment.

00:07:26.874 --> 00:07:29.290 align:middle line:84%
And that comes from the microbes
that we have in our body.

00:07:29.290 --> 00:07:30.820 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And they've
been around for--

00:07:30.820 --> 00:07:31.260 align:middle line:90%
>>ROM: Millions--

00:07:31.260 --> 00:07:32.720 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But let's talk
about the very beginning.

00:07:32.720 --> 00:07:33.379 align:middle line:90%
The beginning.

00:07:33.379 --> 00:07:35.170 align:middle line:84%
>>ROM: So at the very
beginning, this Earth

00:07:35.170 --> 00:07:37.835 align:middle line:90%
is 4.5 billion years old.

00:07:37.835 --> 00:07:40.180 align:middle line:84%
It took the Earth
a billion years

00:07:40.180 --> 00:07:42.790 align:middle line:84%
to cool down enough
for the first organisms

00:07:42.790 --> 00:07:44.250 align:middle line:90%
to live in the Earth.

00:07:44.250 --> 00:07:46.190 align:middle line:84%
So the first organisms
on this Earth

00:07:46.190 --> 00:07:48.960 align:middle line:84%
were unicellular organisms,
and they were basically

00:07:48.960 --> 00:07:50.070 align:middle line:90%
the bacteria.

00:07:50.070 --> 00:07:53.050 align:middle line:84%
And science has found out
now that space dust coming

00:07:53.050 --> 00:07:56.210 align:middle line:84%
from space are all
particles of bacteria.

00:07:56.210 --> 00:07:57.700 align:middle line:84%
And when they landed
on this Earth,

00:07:57.700 --> 00:08:00.680 align:middle line:84%
they were the first organisms
to actually colonize

00:08:00.680 --> 00:08:02.240 align:middle line:90%
this Earth, the bacteria.

00:08:02.240 --> 00:08:06.180 align:middle line:84%
And the bacteria actually had
little bacteria on top of them,

00:08:06.180 --> 00:08:08.280 align:middle line:84%
and those little bacteria
actually had viruses.

00:08:08.280 --> 00:08:12.610 align:middle line:84%
So the bacteria actually have
viruses infecting the bacteria.

00:08:12.610 --> 00:08:15.000 align:middle line:84%
And there was no fungi,
there's no parasites,

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:18.480 align:middle line:84%
it was just bacteria and viruses
that were living on this Earth.

00:08:18.480 --> 00:08:21.670 align:middle line:84%
And four 3 billion
years-- the Earth

00:08:21.670 --> 00:08:24.510 align:middle line:90%
is 4.5 billion years old, OK.

00:08:24.510 --> 00:08:29.830 align:middle line:84%
From 1 billion years
to 3.5 billion years,

00:08:29.830 --> 00:08:32.476 align:middle line:84%
only the bacteria
lived on this Earth.

00:08:32.476 --> 00:08:34.600 align:middle line:84%
And the only things-- they
only thought two things.

00:08:34.600 --> 00:08:35.440 align:middle line:90%
Can I eat you?

00:08:35.440 --> 00:08:37.350 align:middle line:90%
Can you eat me?

00:08:37.350 --> 00:08:40.049 align:middle line:84%
And they looked at this
Earth-- they basically

00:08:40.049 --> 00:08:43.590 align:middle line:84%
looked at every place on this
Earth, they either lived in it

00:08:43.590 --> 00:08:45.140 align:middle line:90%
or they broke it down to eat it.

00:08:45.140 --> 00:08:46.640 align:middle line:84%
That's the only
thing that they did.

00:08:46.640 --> 00:08:49.110 align:middle line:84%
They said, oh, there's
not a bacteria that's

00:08:49.110 --> 00:08:51.870 align:middle line:84%
living in this particular
strata of Earth,

00:08:51.870 --> 00:08:53.810 align:middle line:84%
I guess I'm going to
set up camp there.

00:08:53.810 --> 00:08:54.972 align:middle line:90%
I can live on rocks.

00:08:54.972 --> 00:08:55.680 align:middle line:90%
Well, guess what?

00:08:55.680 --> 00:08:56.700 align:middle line:90%
I can live in water.

00:08:56.700 --> 00:08:57.450 align:middle line:90%
Or guess what?

00:08:57.450 --> 00:08:59.070 align:middle line:90%
I can live somewhere else.

00:08:59.070 --> 00:09:00.780 align:middle line:90%
I can live in the heat.

00:09:00.780 --> 00:09:04.762 align:middle line:84%
You actually find bacteria in
the most extreme temperatures

00:09:04.762 --> 00:09:06.720 align:middle line:84%
of the Earth because they
can live in anything.

00:09:06.720 --> 00:09:08.930 align:middle line:90%
They could break down anything.

00:09:08.930 --> 00:09:13.060 align:middle line:84%
We find bacteria breaking down
the nuclear waste of Chernobyl.

00:09:13.060 --> 00:09:15.230 align:middle line:84%
When you actually
walked in Chernobyl,

00:09:15.230 --> 00:09:18.784 align:middle line:84%
there's black slime inside
the nuclear reactor.

00:09:18.784 --> 00:09:20.200 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: They're
doing their job.

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:23.282 align:middle line:84%
They're actually neutralizing,
or consuming, radiation.

00:09:23.282 --> 00:09:24.740 align:middle line:84%
>>ROM: They're
consuming radiation.

00:09:24.740 --> 00:09:25.740 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Nuclear waste.

00:09:25.740 --> 00:09:27.530 align:middle line:84%
>>ROM: Yeah, they
can consume anything.

00:09:27.530 --> 00:09:33.740 align:middle line:84%
And in the 1970s, there
was this huge accident

00:09:33.740 --> 00:09:36.200 align:middle line:84%
that happened in the
Love Canal in New York.

00:09:36.200 --> 00:09:36.910 align:middle line:90%
Remember that?

00:09:36.910 --> 00:09:37.310 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I remember that, yes.

00:09:37.310 --> 00:09:39.935 align:middle line:84%
>>ROM: It was actually the birth
of the environmental movement.

00:09:39.935 --> 00:09:41.970 align:middle line:84%
You know the Indian
with the tearing eye?

00:09:41.970 --> 00:09:43.700 align:middle line:84%
That was because
of the Love Canal.

00:09:43.700 --> 00:09:49.070 align:middle line:84%
And the Love Canal was because
a chemical company, unnamed, had

00:09:49.070 --> 00:09:53.590 align:middle line:84%
buried transistors
and-- big transistors,

00:09:53.590 --> 00:10:01.010 align:middle line:84%
the kind that had dioxin
and PBBs and PCBs up

00:10:01.010 --> 00:10:02.267 align:middle line:90%
on the telephone poles.

00:10:02.267 --> 00:10:03.350 align:middle line:90%
And they just buried them.

00:10:03.350 --> 00:10:05.500 align:middle line:84%
And it slowly leaked
out into the ground.

00:10:05.500 --> 00:10:07.250 align:middle line:84%
And it leaked out so
much that the frogs

00:10:07.250 --> 00:10:08.600 align:middle line:90%
started growing three heads.

00:10:08.600 --> 00:10:11.970 align:middle line:84%
And it was like, no big
deal, until babies started

00:10:11.970 --> 00:10:15.090 align:middle line:84%
to have malformations and
congenital deformities.

00:10:15.090 --> 00:10:17.326 align:middle line:84%
And so the government
said, wow, we

00:10:17.326 --> 00:10:18.950 align:middle line:84%
need to start doing
something like this

00:10:18.950 --> 00:10:20.760 align:middle line:84%
because this is all
over the United States.

00:10:20.760 --> 00:10:25.010 align:middle line:84%
And that was the first
Superfund site that happened.

00:10:25.010 --> 00:10:27.860 align:middle line:84%
And so the government of New
York and the United States

00:10:27.860 --> 00:10:31.970 align:middle line:84%
government actually put
the biggest punitive damage

00:10:31.970 --> 00:10:35.400 align:middle line:84%
awards towards the state of
New York against this chemical

00:10:35.400 --> 00:10:39.430 align:middle line:84%
company, and it was like
$10 billion or something

00:10:39.430 --> 00:10:41.350 align:middle line:90%
like that to clean the site up.

00:10:41.350 --> 00:10:44.200 align:middle line:84%
And because of all the lawyers
and the legal wranglings,

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:49.930 align:middle line:84%
it actually took 10 years to get
this to come out into the open.

00:10:49.930 --> 00:10:55.640 align:middle line:84%
So during that time, scientists
kept monitoring the Love Canal.

00:10:55.640 --> 00:10:58.880 align:middle line:84%
And over a five year span,
this young scientist came in

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:02.040 align:middle line:84%
and he started measuring
the PCB levels, which

00:11:02.040 --> 00:11:04.270 align:middle line:90%
had a 50,000 year half life.

00:11:04.270 --> 00:11:06.280 align:middle line:84%
The scientist's
like, there's no way

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:09.430 align:middle line:84%
that this thing is
going to get broken

00:11:09.430 --> 00:11:11.080 align:middle line:90%
down enough in our lifetime.

00:11:11.080 --> 00:11:14.830 align:middle line:84%
And these scientists from
the chemical company--

00:11:14.830 --> 00:11:17.210 align:middle line:84%
they sent scientists in,
they said five years later,

00:11:17.210 --> 00:11:20.240 align:middle line:84%
why don't you just measure the
PBB levels and the PCB levels

00:11:20.240 --> 00:11:22.290 align:middle line:90%
there another time.

00:11:22.290 --> 00:11:25.414 align:middle line:84%
And the scientist's like,
it's just a waste of my time.

00:11:25.414 --> 00:11:26.830 align:middle line:84%
In fact, if anything
there's going

00:11:26.830 --> 00:11:29.230 align:middle line:84%
to be more because
of all the leakage.

00:11:29.230 --> 00:11:32.260 align:middle line:84%
But they went in there, there
was a significant decrease--

00:11:32.260 --> 00:11:36.880 align:middle line:84%
there was like a 25%
decrease in PBBs and PCBs.

00:11:36.880 --> 00:11:39.770 align:middle line:84%
And the scientist is
like, wait a minute.

00:11:39.770 --> 00:11:41.884 align:middle line:90%
Something's breaking this down.

00:11:41.884 --> 00:11:43.050 align:middle line:90%
I mean it's not dissipating.

00:11:43.050 --> 00:11:44.860 align:middle line:84%
It's not breaking
down by itself.

00:11:44.860 --> 00:11:47.540 align:middle line:84%
Something is actively
breaking this down.

00:11:47.540 --> 00:11:52.130 align:middle line:84%
And what they did was
they looked at the muck

00:11:52.130 --> 00:11:55.450 align:middle line:90%
in the bottom of the river.

00:11:55.450 --> 00:11:59.690 align:middle line:84%
They found out that microbes
were breaking down the PBBs.

00:11:59.690 --> 00:12:04.320 align:middle line:84%
It is now a science called
Bacterial and Bioremediation.

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:07.000 align:middle line:84%
So every time there's an
oil spill that happens,

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:10.060 align:middle line:84%
we don't clean it up any
more like the Exxon Valdez.

00:12:10.060 --> 00:12:13.570 align:middle line:84%
We just throw microbes at it
because they will eat the oil.

00:12:13.570 --> 00:12:19.690 align:middle line:84%
And fortunately for us, when the
Gulf blew up with the oil spill

00:12:19.690 --> 00:12:23.150 align:middle line:84%
there, there were natural
microbes already eating that.

00:12:23.150 --> 00:12:25.310 align:middle line:84%
And believe it or
not, the dispersants

00:12:25.310 --> 00:12:27.220 align:middle line:84%
that they threw
in there actually

00:12:27.220 --> 00:12:30.790 align:middle line:84%
helped the microbes eat
the oil better and faster,

00:12:30.790 --> 00:12:32.320 align:middle line:90%
because it actually disperses--

00:12:32.320 --> 00:12:32.860 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, interesting.

00:12:32.860 --> 00:12:33.950 align:middle line:84%
Because there was a
lot of controversy

00:12:33.950 --> 00:12:34.730 align:middle line:90%
around those dispersants.

00:12:34.730 --> 00:12:34.802 align:middle line:90%
>>ROM: Yeah.

00:12:34.802 --> 00:12:37.010 align:middle line:84%
There was a lot of controversy
around the dispersants

00:12:37.010 --> 00:12:39.140 align:middle line:84%
because it got into
the bloodstream.

00:12:39.140 --> 00:12:42.950 align:middle line:84%
But there was a
silver lining to that,

00:12:42.950 --> 00:12:45.860 align:middle line:84%
and the microbes actually
broke them down even more.

00:12:45.860 --> 00:12:50.140 align:middle line:84%
And another thing was that
the PBBs and the PCBs,

00:12:50.140 --> 00:12:53.740 align:middle line:84%
they were actually broken
down not just by one microbe,

00:12:53.740 --> 00:12:56.700 align:middle line:84%
it was actually broken down
by a community of microbes.

00:12:56.700 --> 00:12:58.600 align:middle line:84%
In nature, nature
works by community.

00:12:58.600 --> 00:13:03.100 align:middle line:84%
Nature doesn't work by
just one person, right?

00:13:03.100 --> 00:13:07.760 align:middle line:84%
To me having one
company form a monopoly

00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:10.460 align:middle line:84%
and kind of like towering
over their competition,

00:13:10.460 --> 00:13:13.317 align:middle line:90%
it doesn't work in nature.

00:13:13.317 --> 00:13:15.900 align:middle line:84%
You have to have a whole bunch
of companies working in concert

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:19.110 align:middle line:84%
together to create
a real economy.

00:13:19.110 --> 00:13:23.810 align:middle line:84%
So with this economy and this
system, it worked like this.

00:13:23.810 --> 00:13:27.320 align:middle line:84%
It worked like there was one
microbe that saw the PBBs.

00:13:27.320 --> 00:13:29.810 align:middle line:84%
It wasn't a very
big microbe, and it

00:13:29.810 --> 00:13:31.970 align:middle line:84%
wasn't the most
populated microbe.

00:13:31.970 --> 00:13:34.180 align:middle line:84%
It was this one
little tiny microbe

00:13:34.180 --> 00:13:39.130 align:middle line:84%
that basically made its
living one microbe at a time

00:13:39.130 --> 00:13:41.810 align:middle line:84%
versus all the 10,000,
10 million microbes

00:13:41.810 --> 00:13:43.100 align:middle line:90%
that are out there.

00:13:43.100 --> 00:13:45.730 align:middle line:90%
But it ate PBBs and PCBs.

00:13:45.730 --> 00:13:49.300 align:middle line:84%
And it ate it where it
only ate one bond of it.

00:13:49.300 --> 00:13:52.370 align:middle line:84%
And its excrement
was PBB plus one,

00:13:52.370 --> 00:13:55.100 align:middle line:84%
because it only
ate one electron.

00:13:55.100 --> 00:13:58.340 align:middle line:84%
So its excrement was
actually out there,

00:13:58.340 --> 00:14:01.860 align:middle line:84%
and then another microbe
goes, wow, PBB plus one.

00:14:01.860 --> 00:14:03.189 align:middle line:90%
I think I can eat that.

00:14:03.189 --> 00:14:04.605 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So it
ate the excrement.

00:14:04.605 --> 00:14:07.460 align:middle line:84%
>>ROM: It ate the
excrement and its excrement

00:14:07.460 --> 00:14:09.404 align:middle line:84%
became food for
the next microbe.

00:14:09.404 --> 00:14:10.320 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Interesting.

00:14:10.320 --> 00:14:13.180 align:middle line:84%
>>ROM: It became a
whole chain of microbes

00:14:13.180 --> 00:14:15.160 align:middle line:84%
that started to eat
this in concert.

00:14:15.160 --> 00:14:18.360 align:middle line:84%
And they were actually eating
the excrement of each other.

00:14:18.360 --> 00:14:21.345 align:middle line:84%
It happens in
nature all the time.

00:14:21.345 --> 00:14:23.470 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So that's what's
happening in our bodies.

00:14:23.470 --> 00:14:25.345 align:middle line:84%
>>ROM: That's what's
happening in our bodies.

00:14:25.345 --> 00:14:29.286 align:middle line:84%
When we eat food in our
bodies, the first person

00:14:29.286 --> 00:14:31.160 align:middle line:84%
that eats the food are
actually the microbes.

00:14:31.160 --> 00:14:32.285 align:middle line:90%
It isn't us.

00:14:32.285 --> 00:14:33.910 align:middle line:84%
It's the microbes
that actually eat it.

00:14:33.910 --> 00:14:37.021 align:middle line:84%
We cannot eat food and digest
food unless the microbes digest

00:14:37.021 --> 00:14:37.520 align:middle line:90%
it first.

00:14:37.520 --> 00:14:38.520 align:middle line:90%
They get first dibs.

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:40.561 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And so they're
going through this break

00:14:40.561 --> 00:14:43.290 align:middle line:84%
down, this excreting,
and then other microbes

00:14:43.290 --> 00:14:44.590 align:middle line:90%
are consuming that.

00:14:44.590 --> 00:14:46.730 align:middle line:84%
I assume there are chemical
reactions within that?

00:14:46.730 --> 00:14:47.230 align:middle line:90%
>>ROM: Yeah.

00:14:47.230 --> 00:14:48.849 align:middle line:90%
There are chemical reactions.

00:14:48.849 --> 00:14:50.390 align:middle line:84%
There are things
that are being made.

00:14:50.390 --> 00:14:52.315 align:middle line:84%
There are antioxidants
that are being made.

00:14:52.315 --> 00:14:53.940 align:middle line:84%
There are vitamins
that are being made.

00:14:53.940 --> 00:14:56.540 align:middle line:84%
The only reason why we
have 20 essential vitamins

00:14:56.540 --> 00:14:59.170 align:middle line:84%
is because there isn't
bacteria to create those 20

00:14:59.170 --> 00:15:00.670 align:middle line:90%
essential vitamins.

00:15:00.670 --> 00:15:02.390 align:middle line:84%
If we didn't have
bacteria in our bodies,

00:15:02.390 --> 00:15:04.600 align:middle line:84%
we'd have 10,000
essential vitamins

00:15:04.600 --> 00:15:06.860 align:middle line:84%
that we would need
in our bodies.

00:15:06.860 --> 00:15:09.084 align:middle line:84%
The other 10,000 are
made by all the microbes.

00:15:09.084 --> 00:15:10.500 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So now
what happens when

00:15:10.500 --> 00:15:12.810 align:middle line:84%
we start looking at the
whole cleanliness issue?

00:15:12.810 --> 00:15:15.520 align:middle line:84%
I mean, keep the
baby off the floor.

00:15:15.520 --> 00:15:17.840 align:middle line:84%
Don't let the baby crawl
around on a dirty floor,

00:15:17.840 --> 00:15:18.930 align:middle line:90%
put things in its mouth.

00:15:18.930 --> 00:15:20.880 align:middle line:84%
And we have fruit
and vegetable wash

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:23.060 align:middle line:84%
to make sure anything
that's on our vegetables--

00:15:23.060 --> 00:15:25.880 align:middle line:84%
even the organic ones--
they're nice and clean.

00:15:25.880 --> 00:15:28.660 align:middle line:84%
What about the notion of
this kind of cleanliness?

00:15:28.660 --> 00:15:30.200 align:middle line:84%
>>ROM: You're talking
about hygiene.

00:15:30.200 --> 00:15:33.392 align:middle line:84%
And, yes, hygiene
is very important.

00:15:33.392 --> 00:15:36.280 align:middle line:84%
We need to keep the
bad microbes off of us,

00:15:36.280 --> 00:15:38.460 align:middle line:84%
but we also have to
keep in mind that we

00:15:38.460 --> 00:15:41.950 align:middle line:84%
can't go so far that we
actually kill the good microbes.

00:15:41.950 --> 00:15:45.440 align:middle line:84%
And in order to understand
that, let's go back

00:15:45.440 --> 00:15:47.180 align:middle line:84%
to the beginning
of our conversation

00:15:47.180 --> 00:15:49.290 align:middle line:84%
when the Earth was
a billion years old

00:15:49.290 --> 00:15:52.050 align:middle line:84%
and the first microbes
started to colonize the Earth.

00:15:52.050 --> 00:15:55.670 align:middle line:84%
And the microbes lived on
this Earth for over 2 and 1/2

00:15:55.670 --> 00:15:59.960 align:middle line:84%
billion years before the first
multicellular organism, called

00:15:59.960 --> 00:16:02.250 align:middle line:90%
the algae, colonized the Earth.

00:16:02.250 --> 00:16:06.020 align:middle line:84%
So this higher life form
went into the Earth--

00:16:06.020 --> 00:16:09.830 align:middle line:84%
and the microbes have been
here for over 2 billion years.

00:16:09.830 --> 00:16:12.030 align:middle line:84%
And they were saying, I can
eat you, you can eat me,

00:16:12.030 --> 00:16:13.750 align:middle line:90%
we can break everything down.

00:16:13.750 --> 00:16:16.390 align:middle line:84%
And the first higher organism,
the algae, came in there

00:16:16.390 --> 00:16:18.550 align:middle line:90%
and said, hey, you know what?

00:16:18.550 --> 00:16:20.110 align:middle line:90%
I'm more evolved that you guys.

00:16:20.110 --> 00:16:22.830 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to come in and I'm
just going to set up shop.

00:16:22.830 --> 00:16:24.870 align:middle line:84%
And the microbes are
looking at him like--

00:16:24.870 --> 00:16:28.410 align:middle line:84%
It's like us being in sixth
grade going into a new school,

00:16:28.410 --> 00:16:31.320 align:middle line:84%
and just because we're older
than all the other kids,

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:32.934 align:middle line:84%
we're going to take
over that school.

00:16:32.934 --> 00:16:35.350 align:middle line:84%
But all the other kids, the
fifth graders and the existing

00:16:35.350 --> 00:16:38.100 align:middle line:84%
sixth graders go, we know
who the good teachers are,

00:16:38.100 --> 00:16:39.510 align:middle line:84%
we know who the
bad teachers are.

00:16:39.510 --> 00:16:40.480 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: They know
the lay of the land.

00:16:40.480 --> 00:16:41.520 align:middle line:84%
>>ROM: They know
the lay of the land.

00:16:41.520 --> 00:16:43.270 align:middle line:84%
We know where you're
going to get beat up.

00:16:43.270 --> 00:16:47.266 align:middle line:84%
And basically, new kid,
if you don't serve us,

00:16:47.266 --> 00:16:48.390 align:middle line:90%
we're going to beat you up.

00:16:48.390 --> 00:16:49.920 align:middle line:84%
So what are you
going to do for us?

00:16:49.920 --> 00:16:52.960 align:middle line:84%
And that's what the microbes
did to the lowly algae.

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:56.100 align:middle line:84%
And they basically
said, algae, you either

00:16:56.100 --> 00:16:58.720 align:middle line:84%
serve us or we're
going to eat you.

00:16:58.720 --> 00:17:00.030 align:middle line:90%
What's it going to be?

00:17:00.030 --> 00:17:02.880 align:middle line:84%
And the algae goes,
you know what?

00:17:02.880 --> 00:17:05.460 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to hang out and we're
going to form groups of algae

00:17:05.460 --> 00:17:05.960 align:middle line:90%
together.

00:17:05.960 --> 00:17:07.680 align:middle line:84%
And they actually
formed the first life

00:17:07.680 --> 00:17:09.369 align:middle line:90%
form called the Hydra.

00:17:09.369 --> 00:17:12.069 align:middle line:84%
And the Hydra was a
cylindrical object

00:17:12.069 --> 00:17:15.400 align:middle line:84%
that basically had a
funnel to funnel in water,

00:17:15.400 --> 00:17:18.420 align:middle line:84%
and it had motile feet
that actually moved around.

00:17:18.420 --> 00:17:21.220 align:middle line:84%
And they were the first
kind of like living plants,

00:17:21.220 --> 00:17:24.560 align:middle line:84%
but they were actually
collections of multicellular

00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:27.020 align:middle line:84%
organisms that
actually moved around.

00:17:27.020 --> 00:17:28.650 align:middle line:90%
But microbes lived in them.

00:17:28.650 --> 00:17:31.520 align:middle line:84%
And they were the things that
algae said, hey microbes.

00:17:31.520 --> 00:17:34.500 align:middle line:84%
Why don't you come in here
and we'll protect you.

00:17:34.500 --> 00:17:35.940 align:middle line:84%
We'll be your
vessel so you don't

00:17:35.940 --> 00:17:39.000 align:middle line:84%
have to defend
yourself all the time.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:40.210 align:middle line:90%
And guess what?

00:17:40.210 --> 00:17:42.610 align:middle line:84%
We're going to collect
food for you too.

00:17:42.610 --> 00:17:44.360 align:middle line:84%
We're going to have
this little canal

00:17:44.360 --> 00:17:46.520 align:middle line:84%
and we're going to put
food inside this tube,

00:17:46.520 --> 00:17:47.930 align:middle line:90%
and you guys can eat it first.

00:17:47.930 --> 00:17:50.440 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll have your scraps,
we'll have your excrement.

00:17:50.440 --> 00:17:52.870 align:middle line:84%
And we'll also
move you from place

00:17:52.870 --> 00:17:56.910 align:middle line:84%
to place so you don't have to
expend all your energy moving.

00:17:56.910 --> 00:18:00.430 align:middle line:84%
And that's how the microbes
became the mafia of this Earth.

00:18:00.430 --> 00:18:04.260 align:middle line:84%
And they said, OK, you're
going to work for us now.

00:18:04.260 --> 00:18:05.670 align:middle line:90%
Fast forward to human beings.

00:18:05.670 --> 00:18:08.700 align:middle line:90%
We're just a large hydra.

00:18:08.700 --> 00:18:12.290 align:middle line:84%
We feed the microbes, we
give them a place to eat,

00:18:12.290 --> 00:18:13.759 align:middle line:84%
and we give them
the food to eat.

00:18:13.759 --> 00:18:16.050 align:middle line:84%
We give them a body to stay
in, then they're protected,

00:18:16.050 --> 00:18:17.070 align:middle line:90%
and we move around.

00:18:17.070 --> 00:18:18.610 align:middle line:90%
We do all the work for them.

00:18:18.610 --> 00:18:21.220 align:middle line:84%
They basically play us
like little Wii machines,

00:18:21.220 --> 00:18:23.300 align:middle line:90%
and they tell us what to eat.

00:18:23.300 --> 00:18:25.350 align:middle line:84%
And this is all
scientifically proven.

00:18:25.350 --> 00:18:26.915 align:middle line:84%
You change the
microbes in your body,

00:18:26.915 --> 00:18:28.680 align:middle line:84%
you actually change the
cravings in your body.

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:30.054 align:middle line:84%
The microbes tell
us what to eat,

00:18:30.054 --> 00:18:33.190 align:middle line:84%
they tell us what to think,
they give us our emotions.

00:18:33.190 --> 00:18:34.817 align:middle line:90%
And they also protect us.

00:18:34.817 --> 00:18:36.650 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So this is
huge, because now we're

00:18:36.650 --> 00:18:38.820 align:middle line:84%
looking at a time
when we've been

00:18:38.820 --> 00:18:40.590 align:middle line:90%
genetically engineering food.

00:18:40.590 --> 00:18:43.360 align:middle line:84%
When we've been certainly adding
a huge toxin load to the food

00:18:43.360 --> 00:18:44.170 align:middle line:90%
supplies.

00:18:44.170 --> 00:18:45.500 align:middle line:90%
We have a lot of stress.

00:18:45.500 --> 00:18:48.300 align:middle line:84%
It seems like we're doing a lot
of things that would tick off

00:18:48.300 --> 00:18:49.700 align:middle line:90%
our microbial community.

00:18:49.700 --> 00:18:50.730 align:middle line:90%
>>ROM: That's right.

00:18:50.730 --> 00:18:56.100 align:middle line:84%
And with the age of antibiotics
that started over 80 years ago,

00:18:56.100 --> 00:18:59.270 align:middle line:84%
it's just been killing
off the natural microbes

